{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_irving_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280659757/1927062601/0472.xml":{"full_text":"36\nlEPCO\u2019S NET WttL\nAHEAD OF YEAR AGO\n,j\u00bb ___________\nMay Report Filed\u2014lnstitute\nCommittee Heads Named.\nFinancial Notes.\n<4\nBY EDWARD C. STONE.\nThe May report of the Potomac\nElectric Power Co. filed with the\npublic Utilities Commission reveals\nfa gain of J 19.361.27 in net income in\nfifcomparison with the same month in\n*1926. It also shows substantial gains\njfc gross earnings from operations as\nIjjrell as heavier operating expenses.\nBy summing up the figures for the\nBrst five months of the present year\nIt is found that the power company\u2019s\n\u2018Bet income is far ahead of last year.\nNet earnings this year total $1,303,-\nj\u00a775.46, while for the first five months\n!|n 1926 they amounted to $1,172,555.69,\nfar an increase in 1927 of 5139.619.77.\nGross earnings from operations dur\ning the month of May totaled $677,-\n\u2022024.88, against $626,403.20 in May. 1926.\n.Or an increase in favor of the month\n;jOnder review' of $50,611.65. Operating\nExpenses this year were $313,729.13,\nor a gain of $34,474.88 over May a\niyear ago when thev amounted to\n\u2022<279,254.25.\nNet earnings from operations\nCached the sum of $363,295.75. in com\n;t*parison with a total of $347,158.95\n\u25a0Jast year, leaving a gain this year of\n'<16,136.80. After deductions for ex\n\u2018jpenses, taxes and other demands, the\nijporporation reports a net income for\n\u2022|he month of $215,437.83. compared\n<i\u00bbvith the lower figure a year ago of\n'<<196,076.11.\nFigures for the first five months\n\u2022i|how gross earnings in 1927 from\n\u25a0Operations of $3,621,683.40, compared\ntvith $3,353,638.56 last year, an in\ncrease for the period of $268,044.84.\njWhile earnings have increased, oper\n\u2022\u2022ting expenses have also advanced,\ntotal of $1,524,055.02 being compared\njwith $1,404,862 last year, the exact\nAdditional costs being $124,193.02. Aft\n\u2022r deduction of expenses the com\n\u2019jpany\u2019s net earnings from operations\n\u2019\u2022mounted to $2,092,628.38 this year,\nfar an advance of $143,851.82 over the\ntotal for the same period a year ago\n;pf $1,948,776.56.\nImportant I. A. B. Committees Named.\nv President I. J. Roberts of Washing\nton Chapter, American Institute of\n{Banking, yesterday appointed the\nchairmen of all the important com\nklttees for the coming year. Mr.\nioberts was able to retain in service\nr the institute many members who\nirried on so successfully last year,\ni well as previous to that time. He\nren obtained the promi.se of the re\nring president, T. Hunton Leith, to\ntake change of next year\u2019s annual\nBanquet.\nThe list as announced yesterday\nthat the affairs of the institute\n*\u2022111 ba in charge of the following com\njtpittee heads during the coming year:\nArchieves committee. Miss Lois A.\n\u2022White, Federal-American National\nj lank; athletics committee, G. M. Van\njffoesen. Second National Bank; audit\nCommittee, Raymond P. Lochte, Dis\ntrict National Bank; banquet com\nmittee, T. Hunton Leith, Security Sav\nings Commercial; educational com\nmittee, James A. Soper, Lincoln Na\ntional; forum committee, Harold W.\nBurnside, Farmers and Mechanics\u2019 Na\ntional; house committee, Elmer\nO\u2019Hara, Seventh Street Savings: mem\nbership committee, August E. Hense,\n\u25a0W. B. Hibbs Co.; public affairs and\npublic education committee, E. J. Me-\nQuade, Liberty National; publicity\njoorqmittee, Miss S. W. Burwell, Na\ntional Metropolitan; theater party\ncommittee, A. W. Sherman, American\nSecurity Trust Co.; ways and means\ncommittee, R. Jesse Chaney, Com\nmercial National; women\u2019s committee,\nBiss Mabel V. Royce, Washington\nLoan Trust Co., and editor, \u201cDollars\nand Sense,\u201d Aubrey O. Dooley, Com\npnercia! National.\nThe next big event in institute af\nfairs will be the national convention,\nto be held in Detroit the second week\nin July. Washington Chapter will\n\u2022end a strong delegation and a larger\n<>ne than went to Dallas, Tex., last\njjrear.\nBanking Expenses Up 200 Per Cent.\nO. Howard Wolfe, cashier of the\nPhiladel ph ia-G i rard National Bank,\n\u2022peaking at the Virginia Bankers\u2019\nConvention at Virginia Beach on\nDoorstep Banking Problems,\u201d\ndeclared that a survey had shown that\n\u2022tore than 50 per cent of deposit ac\ncounts in banks were unprofitable to\nthe banks, but that these accounts\nwere responsible for 40 per cent of\nthe bank\u2019s overhead. He declared\nthat bank expenses had increased 100\nper cent in all phases and 200 per cent\n;in some phases in the last 25 years,\nbut that bank earnings had not in\ngreased.\nj \"Banks could throw out all their\n;deposits,\u201d Mr. Wolfe declared, \"and\nthen make larger dividends than they\nlitre making. If you will analyze your\nbusiness you will find that you are\n.\u2022taking your profits on your surplus\nipther than on your deposits.\u201d\nThe association s committee on re\nvision of the State banking laws made\n;l*ie formal report, submitting the pro\nposed bill as drafted by a special com\nijftission, revising and codifying all the\nbanking laws under one act, to be\ndesignated the Virginia banking act.\nThe new bill is regarded as far reach\njfgC in import.\nAs Moody Sees Stocks and Bonds.\n\u201cExpansion of brokers\u2019 loans is per\nhaps taken too seriously, at least\ni(or the moment,\" says Moody\u2019s Re\nlYiew.\nj ;J*\u201cBrokers\u2019 loans and margin buy\ning of stocks normally expand with\n|the growth of wealth and income;\nfifed in proportion to national income\nthey are now probably quite a little\nJiknaller than they were in January,\n2 6.\nl\u00ab:\"On the other hand, now that stock\nare so high that stocks yield\nthird of a point less than com\ntjifeting bonds, hard-headed investors\n'\u2022ife inclined to take profits; and this\nprofit-taking promises to make hard\n*<iledding for a bull movement from\nifpls level. So it is that indications\ntpbint to a horizontal stock market.\u201d\n{CONTRIBUTIONS SOUGHT\nFOR NEEDED OPERATION\npkarmo\u00dft Aid for Consumptives\ni* Bays Patient Requires Treatment.\nBeport Is Made.\n1 7- Contributions to aid in defraying the\n'Cost of an operation for a patient have\n7been requested by the Starmont Aid\n*for Consumptives, whose annual re\n'Jttrt was made public yesterday.\nContributions may be sent the presi\ndent, Mrs. E. J. Brennan, the Logan\niHotel, or the treasurer, Mrs. George\n.Cohan, 1917 Thirty-seventh street.\n.Officers of the organization pointed out\n.that the patient needs the operation,\nAiUt that the organization has not\n\u25a0\u2022nough money to defray the entire\n\u2022ost.\ni The annual report showed that the\nJkarmont Aid for Consumptives has\n><24 members, all volunfeer workers,\nf#d spent but sl2 for its own use last\n|jear. Fifty-two persons were assisted\nduring the year, assistance given in\ncluding such services as the i>ayment\nOs hospital, doctors' and dentists\u2019 bills\n\u2022hd furnishing needed supplies. Cases\njprwe frequently visited, and a special\nheaded by Edith B. Fenton,\n\u2022ided veterans.\nf j::\njActinotherapy is the name given to\ntreatment of disease by ligl t rays.\nSTOCK MARKET TRADE SHRINKS;\nUNFAVORABLE TURN IS FACTOR\nI\nBonds Continue Heavy, Due to Hard List\nof Undigested Offerings in Brokers\u2019\nHands Absorbing Loans.\nBY CHARLES F. SPEARE.\nSpecial Dispatch to Tho Star.\nNEW YORK, June 25.\u2014The propor\ntions of the stock market shrank this\nweek as less confidence was exhibited\nin the \u2018stability of prices for specula\ntive securities.\nEach day witnessed a contest be\ntween the two elements in the mar\nket. with small daily declines in the\nprice average up to Thursday, when\na heavy outpouring of stocks resulted\nin the largest losses since early in\nJune. At the same time, the unfortu\nnate conditions in the bond market\ndeveloped a situation that is respon\nsible for a considerable part of the\nexpansion in the so-called brokers'\nloan account, with the general run of\nclients of the investment banker un\nwilling to purchase new issues at pre\nvailing prices.\nWhile the stock market was react\ning to the number of new develop\nments that were unfavorable, the bond\nmarket continued to reflect a state of\nmind rather than any additional rea\nsons for its vveaknes. There were a\nnumber of indications in the trade re\nviews that production was slowing\ndown and profits declining, with dull\nconditions in some of the major in\ndustries likely to contiue well into\nSummer. The statistics from the iron\nand steel centers point very clearly\nto this. So do those from the metal in\ndustry. There has been no correction\nof the troubles arising out of an over\nproduction of oil. In fact, new pools\nire being discovered almost daily and\npouring their streams into an already\nsaturated market.\nGeneral Outlook Is Good.\nBy and large, however, business is\ngood. If it were not we could not\nhave the record car loadings or the\nbank clearings that are reported\nfrom week to week. Undoubtedly\nthe momentum of nearly three years\nof prosperous trade is carrying the\ncountry along to some extent. This\nmay wear off after a while. When\ncertain of the large industries, such\nas those above mentioned, as well as\ntextiles, woolens, silks, rubber and\nsugar, are eliminated, there remain a\ngreat many others out of which the\ncountry is drawing a large revenue\nand in which millions of people are\nfinding steady and profitable em\nployment.\nA survey of the business outlook\nmade at the recent credit men's con\nvention in Louisville is illuminating.\nThis represents the opinions of 21\ntrade groups and thousands of close\nstudents of business and credit con\nditions. It was the composite opinion\nof those replying to the questionnaire\nthat business in the next three\nmonths will be better, while the pros\npects for the next six months were\nrated higher than for the coming\nthree months. In spite of the current\ncomment on poor collections, these\ncredit experts found that payments in\nMay wore better than in April, and\nquite as satisfactory last month as in\nMay. 1926.\nTop-heavy Stock Market Menace.\nDiscussing the business outlook\nthis week, one of America\u2019s leading\nbankers said: \u201cAfter several months\nof anxiety over the high price of se-\ncurities and the condition of trade, I\nhave come to the conclusion that we\nare so strongly fortified in this\ncountry with money and by credit\nrelations with the rest of the world\nthat business seems fair to remain\non an even keel.\n\u201cThe only fear that I have is that\nstocks will be forced up to prices\nthat will make them topheavy and\nmay some day topple over. Business\nwill be affected more by a break in i\nstocks than by any other factor. The\naverage merchant or manufacturer\ntoday owns securities, and any dis\nturbance in the market for stocks\nwill influence his business policy con\nsiderably.\u201d\nWhat is likely to happen in the\nnext few months is a more or less\ngeneral effort on the part of pro\nducers to bring down their cost of\nproduction. It is significant that the\nindustry which represents more than\nBaltimore Markets\nBALTIMORE, June 25 (Special).\u2014\nDemand for new potatoes continues\ngood, but it takes well graded stock\nto bring top values. Receipts have\nbeen running fairly liberal this week\nand the market has eased off to some\nextent, No. 1 Eastern Shore potatoes\nbringing 4.00a4.25 barrel, and York\nRiver and Norfolk Hampton selling at\n3.75a4.00; No. 2 stock, as well as spot\nted and heated potatoes, sell mostly\n1.50a2.00, as to quality and condition.\nOld potatoes continue In ample receipt\nand the demand for all grades is easily\nsatisfied, the market ruling early at\n3.00a3.50 per 100 pounds, and 2.00a\n2.50 for No. 2 demand centered on\nwell graded sound stock, the season\nbeing well advanced, and culls are\nnot wanted at any price.\nNative and nearby garden truck\ncontinues to show seasonable increase\nand while demand is generally fair on\nall lines, only first-class produce will\nbring top values at the following\nquotations: Asparagus, 2.50a3.50 dozen\nfor choice to fancy green, while partly\nwhite and culls will not bring over\n1.50a2.25; stringless green beans, 1.25a\n1.50 bushel, and wax beans, 1.00a1.25;\nbeets and radishes, 2.00a3.00 per 100;\nblue kale, 50a60 bushel; cabbage, 50a\n75 per iy 2 bushel hamper; carrots,\n3.00a6.00 per 100; lettuce, oOaI.OO\nbushel; Spring onions, 1.25a1,50 per\n100; peas, 50a1.25 bushel, and spinach,\n40 to 75 bushel.\nEarly June apples made their ap\npearance on the market this week\nand large smooth stock met with\nready sale at 1.00a2.00 bushel, but\nmost of the stock arriving has been\nsmall and for this class of apples it is\nmore a question of buyer than price.\nEastern Shore blackberries in good\ndemand at Bals, while strawberries\ncontinue in fair demand at Bal6.\nClosing grain quotations: Wheat,\nNo. 2 red Winter, spot, 1.47 \u00bbA; No. 2\nred Winter garlicky, spot, 1.44%.\nCorn, No. 2, domestic, 1.06a1,07. Cob\ncorn, 5.00 per barrel. Oats, No. 3,\nwhite, spot, 56. Rye, nearby, 1.05a1.10.\nEgg Prices Increase.\nReceipts of native and nearby eggs\nhave been only fair this week and\nwhile trading on the exchange has\nbeen light, there has been a good con-\nsumptive movement and the market\nholds firm at 23% cents a dozen for j\nfirsts in free cases, an advance of 2 j\ncents a dozen over opening prices\nMonday. Buyers are very critical as j\nto quality, however, during the Sum\nmer season and it takes first class well\ngraded stock to bring top values. With\na three-day holiday the coming week\nend the demand will be good and\nprompt and liberal shipments are\nadvisable.\nLive Poultry Quotations.\nReceipts of Spring chickens have\nbeen light this week, especially of\nstock weighing two pounds and over,\nand the market is firm, but shows j\nlittle change in values. An active\nmarket is looked for next week, owing\nto the Fourth of July holiday, and\nmore liberal shipments are advisable\nas the market will continue firm with\npossibly an increase in price. Demand\nwill be best for Springers averaging\ntwo pounds and over and shipment of\nsmall undersized stock not advisable\nas it tends to lo\\j\u00bbr the values of the\nlarger birds. Thi market closed to\nTHE SUNDAY STAR, WASHINGTON, D. C.. JUNE 26, 1927-PART T.\nany other a non-essential should have\nbeen the one this week to originate\nsuch a policy. Except in the field of\ntransportation, there have been few\n\u2666instances this year where radical wage\ndemands have been successful. This\nis an evidence that employment is\nbeing sought and that there is a sur\nplus in the labor market.\nBond Market Badly Glutted.\nIt is seme years since a condition\nsuch as exists in the investment mar\nket hoda.v has occurred. It was esti\nmated this week that there were\n5700,000,000 of unsold new issues in\noriginal hands. This figure is un\ndoubtedly too high, but the sum is\nlarge enough to have a very direct\nbearing on bank loans. In a sense\nbuyers\u2019 of bonds are on a strike against\npresent prices. There is no prospect\nof improvement until the level of\nprices,; for new issues particularly,\ndrops bo the point where the invest\ning public becomes interested.\nThe supply of new bonds has fallen\noff somewhat, but the market for for\neign bonds and for many of the new\ndomestic industrial issues has been\nvery mtich upset. Restricted output\nand the closer balance of the opinions\nof the hanker and his client on the\nquestion of value are necessary before\nthis condition will he corrected.\nIt will be helped, of course, by a\nseason of moderate money rates. Al\nthough'time loans this week advanced\nto 4% per cent, after being as low as\n4 l per cent in the Spring, there is\nno suggestion of firm money. During\nthe July* 1 disbursement period, call\nloans wOl undoubtedly advance, with\nrenewal .rates for a few days at 4**\nper cent and possibly as high as 5\nper ugnt. From then on until the\nIst or tbe> 15th of August, money\nwill concentrate in the New York mar\nket and should be extremely easy, as\nsuming tltere is no withdrawal of gold\nfrom this country for French account.\nAfter the middle of August and until\nNovember' rates are likely to advance\nagain. T.be entire money situation\nwould, of cjp<urse. be affected adversely\nby a continued increase in brokers\u2019\nloans, due tbo an accumulation of un\nsold bonds, 'and, on the other hand,\nfavorably l\u00bby a severe break in the\nstock market, releasing funds from\nspeculative commitments.\nIt is moreprobable that the usual\nplay of events surrounding the mar\nket will havia a larger influence this\nSummer and, than others of ex\ntraordinary character.\nCrop Onillook Unimproved.\nThe crop situation, so far as Winter\nwheat and conns are concerned, has not\nimproved. Continued rains have low\nered the averages for both crops.\nHowever, the -outlook for cotton is\nbetter. Where* there were fears for\nthis year\u2019s grqwth a few weeks ago,\nthere is no warn expectation of a high\nly satisfactory {return when the sea\nson closes this SFall.\nFrai.ce continues to adjust her\nfinancial conditions, the government\nsteadily reducing} its debt to the Bank\nof France, builcfiing up foreign bal\nances and placing, herself in a posi\ntion to stabilize Her exchange. Italy,\nhaving followed pier program of ex\nchange stabilization around 6% cents\nwith a series of decrees reduc\ning rents, wagls and the middleman\u2019s\nprofits to conform\u2018With exchange, has\nthis week faced a. runaway market\nagain in the lira, which may bring\nsome embarrassment to the govern\nment. k\nThings are not \\qoing so well in\nGermany, in domestlj: or foreign trade,\nor in finances. Thei|p has been an ex\ntravagant governmroiit and municipal\nadministration for ttyy last two years,\nwhich has called foti comment from\nthe American agent tfnneral of repara\ntions, who critizes thie\u00bb German budget\nand calls attention to the acueeness\nof the problem arising out of increas\ning governmental expenditures. In\nthe next two months transfers of repa\nrations of between 300,000,000 and\n300,000,000 gold marks ;inust be made.\nIt is possible that ne<v German dol\nlars loans will be negotiated to assist\nin this transfer.\nday at 26 to 38 cents \\a pound for\nstock weighing two pounds and over\nwith white Leghorns soiling at the\nlower values, while chick ens weigh\ning under two pounds at 22 to 35\nas to size and quality. Mast ket for old\nhens continues easy at 20l to 26 for\nstock weighing 3 1 pounds! and over,\nwhile smaller fowl and Leghorns are\nslow sale at 16 to 18. Old boosters in\nample supply and draggy atA 12 to 15.\nDemand for ducks only fairt at 24 to\n27 for large fat stock 4 pufends and\nover, while smaller ducks will not\nbring over 20 to 22 and t\u00abW ducks\nare neglected at 15 to 20. pigeons\ncontinue in fair demand at 20*jto 30 a\npair for both young and oldJt\nCattle Market Steady.\nThe general live cattle market rules\nsteady on first-quality stock, wttich is\nin moderate receipt and good\ndemand. Cattle arriving on. the\nwharves of ordinary quality and\nmoves slow at inside values, \u2018storing\nlambs in more ample receipt and! the\nmarket has an easier tone, with iwices\nmostly in buyers\u2019 favor.\nQuotations today at Light Street\nwharf:\nBeef Cattle\u2014First quality, poumt 9\nto 10; common to medium, 5 to\\ 8;\nbulls, as to quality, 5 to 7. J\nCows\u2014Choice to fancy, 6 to 7; com\nmon tq fair, 3 to 5.\nOxen\u2014As to quality, 5 to 7.\nMilk Cows\u2014Choice to fancy pea\u2019\n:SM; mmon\nCalves\u2014Veal, choice, pound.\nordinary to medium. 9 to 11; rough\nand common, 7 to 8; small culls, 7 to 8\nSheep\u2014Choice. 7; old bucks, 4 to 5;\ncommon, 2 to 3.\nLambs\u2014Spring, choice, 15 to 15U;\noH r t 5 A good 12 to 14; common, thin,\n8 to 10.\nHogs\u2014Straight. 9 to 10; sows, 7 to,8;\nlive pigs, 15 to 20; shoats, 10 to 12.\nPee Gee Paint\nPure Lead, Zinc and Linseed Oil\nMAIN OFFICE\ntwfninaerCo siucsfeSM\nn CAMP MEIGS\nSFadnunJU\nLactobacillus Acidophilus\nCall our iirodurt \"L. A.\u201d Milk\n(Trade Mark)\nFor intefttlnal disorder*\nat *-SK\u25a0 oh.vuleian about It.\nnational vaccine and\nANTITOXIN INSTTUTE\nPhone North 80 1513 U J*t. N.W.\nBumsteadsWormSyrup\n\u201c\".f* 1 merer.\" Where\nrmi n ar f. followed, IT NEVER\n\u20182|\u201e; end enormoua\nSkiLf* .SANTONIN., it contains full doee.\ntert. Sold everywhere\nor br mull, 50c a bottle.\nf C. A. VoorUees. M. D.. PhlladelDhU\nDANDRUFF\nBand scalp eczema\nMillions etc Lucky Tiger. Money-\nSiTV Back Guarantee. Whyte-\nImAFox knocks skin troubles.\nkKjMfAt Barbers end Druggists.\nJftLUCKYTIGER\nBUSINESS IS SLOW\nIN STEEL INDUSTRY\nSteadier Tone Develops in\nCopper Market \u2014Tin\nMoves Irregularly.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, June 25\u2014In the steel\nmarket during the week some addi\ntional contracts were placed by the\nrailroads and reports were of fail\nstructural steel contracts pending, but\notherwise business was slow and rep\nresented seasonal conditions. Mills, in\nmany instances, again reduced pro\nduction. Quotations presented little\nchange, but. with the exception of\nsheets, it seemed possible to shade\nselling levels to some extent. Pig iron\nwas dull and prices unsettled.\nSteadier tone has developed In the\ncopper market. Recent offerings at\nthe 12-cent level appear to have been\nabsorbed with a considerable volume\nof business reported. Consumers were\nsaid to be in the market for additional\nsupplies at that figure, but producers\ngenerally showed increased confidence\nlate in the week and were reported\nholding electrolytic for 12% cents, de\nlivered at Connecticut Valley points.\nThe demand abroad has continued\nquiet, being chiefly in small lots.\nPrices for refined products have been\nreduced t* to cents per pound.\nTin price fluctuations were irregu\nlar, with easiness prevailing late in\nthe week. London was lower and con\nsuming demand here was small.\nLead was steadier and producers re\nported a little better consuming de\nmand for June and July positions.\nZinc remained quiet with prices\nsteady. Ore was advanced and sales\nwere said to have been the largest in\nsome time.\nAntimony was a shade easier, large\nly as a result of the absence of con\nsuming demand. Cables told of re\nduced production In China and strong\nly held stocks.\ncottHMly\nAFTER EARLY DROP\nGeneral Market Ends Steady.\nGood Part of Gain Lost\nat Close.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, June 25.\u2014Prospects\nfor a renewal of showers in the cotton\nbelt over Sunday led to rallies from\nan opening decline in the cotton\nmarket today. October sold up from\n16.85 to 16.99 or 7 points net higher,\nbut there was a spurt of realizing in\nthe last few minutes and it closed at\n16.91. The general market closed\nsteady, net 4 points higher to 1 point\nlower.\nThe opening was steady at a decline\nof 1 to 4 points. Active months showed\nnet losses of about 5 to 8 points in\nearly trading under liquidation, pro\nmoted by favorable early weather re\nports. The map showed less rain in\nthe belt than it has for some time,\nand the trade seemed hopeful of the\ndry warm weather which is said to\nbe much needed over the South.\nOfferings were comparatively light,\nhowever, and the forenoon market\nfirmed up on the official forecast for\nshowers in most sections of the belt.\nJuly contracts which had sold off to\n16.50 advanced to 16.64, while Decem\nber rallied from 17.08 to 17.23, net\nadvances of about 7 to 9 points on\nthe general list.\nBuying was held in check by con\ntinued uncertainty as to the effect\nof possible notices on Tuesday, or by\nthe usual week end consideration, and\nthe market lost a good part of its\ngain during the last few minutes.\nJuly was relatively steady during the\ngreater part of the morning, com\npared with later months narrowing\nslightly, as if previous liquidation had\nImproved its technical position and\nleft it a little more sensitive to cov\nering by shorts. At the close, July\nseemed to be about 32 points under\nOctober, compared with a closing dif\nference of 37 points on Friday.\nThe amount of cotton on shipboard\nawaiting clearance at the end of the\nweek was estimated at 107,000 bales\nagainst 25,000 last year.\nPrivate cables reported trade call\ning in Liverpool and that continental\ninterests were buying July in the\nmarket there against sales of later\nmonths.\nA report by a New Orleans au\nthority placed the condition of the\nTexas crop at 77.7 based on reports\nfrom correspondents as of June 20.\nDivorce is most likely during the\nthird and fourth years after marriage,\npoints out an answered question in the\nLiberty magazine. Court records, it\nexplains, show that 9.3 per cent of\nall divorces In the United States oc\ncur after four years of marriage; 9.2\nper cent after three years.\nM7MUIMD\nJjISYES EXAMINED\nA GLASSES FITTED\nU Kinsman Uptical Ga\nII 70514th St N.W.\nI VBraneh Store, 3016 14th\nPHONE MAIN 292\nI Real Estate\ni Loans\nI (D. C. Property Only)\n6%\nNo Commission Charged\ncan take 12 years to\npay* off your loan without\nthe expense of renewing.\nSLOtO for $lO per month,\ninchitling interest and prin\ncipal Larger or smaller\nloa r\u00a3 s at proportionate\nrates..\nPERPETUAL\nBUILDING\nASSOCIATION\nLarge.'V in Washington\nAssets CWer $15,000,000.00\nCor. lib and E N.W.\nD. C. Naval Reserve\nAnnual cruise plans for the first\ncontingent of Naval Reservists who\nwill go aboard the U. S. destroyer\nAllen, their training ship, have prac\ntically been completed, and it appears\nI now that the 2d Division, which\nwill be the first to go, will carry the\nlargest contingent ever taken from\nthis city for training at sea. The ves\nsel will sail from the Washington\nNavy Yard on July 2, and all of the\nofficers who will make this trip al\nready have received their orders\nfrom the Navy Department to report\naboard to Lieut. Comdr. Wolfe, com\nmanding the ship.\nThe officers from Washington will\nbe Lieut. Harry J. Nichols, executive\nofficer of the local battalion, who also\nwill be executive officer of the Allen\nduring the cruise, and probably also\nwill be assigned the duties as naviga\ntor; Lieut. Paul V. Thompson, who\nwill be engineer officer; Lieut. Wilbert\nE. Locklin, Lieut. J. F. Moore, who\ncommands the second division. En\nsign VV. D. David and Chief Radio\nElectrician F. V. Monar. In addition,\nthere will be five officers from the\nNaval Reserve contingent in Balti\nmore. Md.\nForty-seven enlisted men have sig\nnified their intention of making this\nfirst cruise, which, together with the\n30 Washington men assigned as ship\nkeepers, will make a total of 77 men\nfrom Washington. The remainder of\nthe complement of the vessel will be\nmade up of enlisted men from the\nBaltimore Reserve, who will come\nhere to hoard the vessel, which will go\nout for two weeks of maneuvers and\noperations with the Atlantic Scouting\nFleet destroyers, off New York and\nNewport.\nThe 2d Division is being given\nas much advantage as possible in the\nland-training schedule right now in\norder that its routine will be\n1 smoothed out by the time It gets\nn. American Furniture Co.\nlandise at Prices Less Than Cheaper\nt Terms to Suit Your Convenience\nI No Telephone, C. O.D. or MaU Orders; We place on sale tomorrow 29 most beautiful HA nn mil\n1- a Living Room Suites\u2014actual $l9B values\u2014your choice 1\nWe place on sale tomorrow 16 beautiful 10-piece ACI 00 I s I\ndining room suites. Actual $189.00 values. Choice, 1 j \"\"\"\"\"\"I v\nF _2- MWe place on sale tomorrow 14 splendid Four-piece\nHilfrsom 4\u00ablle. AhmJ stM.l.v.lun. V'lur sns.oo\nWe place on sale tomorrow S Bed-Davenport Suites. CJE 00 place on\nActual $79.00 values. Your choice \u00ab3nr\u00ab)\u00bbVV Fiber Suites. Actual $55.00 values. Your choice vwJidW\n_. P ,a f e _?\" s^* e tomorrow an We place on sale tomorrow 17 I\nWe place on sale tomorrow 19 Five-piece odd lot of Fiber Rockers. Actual periad style Living Room Chairs.\nPainted Breakfast Sets. Different styles. Actual 6JOO CA values ranging up to QC Values ranging up to Ct O7C\n$39.00 values. Your choice $12.50 Your choice vv#W 129.00. Your choice....\nn AMBR'CAKi\niff AMERICAN fURNUTOCQH\nNINTH STREET, N.W.\nINTER-OCEAN 7 BETWEEN\nI BUILDINO V y E ANoF STS\naboard the vessel, and particular ef\nforts have been made to perfect the\ngun crews and fire-control parties to\nthe end that the local Reservists will\nbe the first year that the Reservists\nthey fire the guns aboard the Allen\nat target practice this year. This will\nhe the first year that the reservists\nhave been called up for target prac\ntice with the big guns since the\nWorld War. and many of the enlisted\npersonnel are youths who have en\nlisted since the war, and they will\nget their first taste of handling and\"\nfiring the big missiles.\nThere is a particular shortage of\nengineer officers for the first cruise,\nit was said, and for this reason Lieut.\nThompson, who is both a deck and\nengineer officer, has been assigned\nto engine room duties because of his\ntraining during the World War. when\nhe w r as chief engineer of one of the\nanti-submarine patrol yachts operat\ning in the Mediterranean.\nFor the subsequent cruisers, it was\nfurther pointed out. there will be\nplenty of engineer officers to fill all\nthe watches.\nPraise for a member of the local\nNaval Reserve, a seaman, second class,\nstudying for commission as an avi\nator in the naval service, is contained\nin a report received at local head\nquarters from the commanding officer\nof the Hampton Roads Naval Air Sta\ntion, where the youth had been under\ngoing training.\nHe received special mention in the\nreport for skill used in making a\nforced landing which resulted in no\ndamage to either plane or occupants,\nafter the elevating controls had car\nried away. The report says that Sea\nman (second class) Gerardus B.\nClarke, while flying at an altitude of\n250 feet, had his elevating controls\nbreak, and by exercising extraordinary\njudgment he brought the plane to the\n1 water by the use of his engine and\nthe use of the horizontal control, thus\nstabilizing the plane and making a\nsafe landing, with no damage to the\ncraft.\nClarke was a member of a class of\nfour, another of whom. Gustavo Hog\nlund, also was from Washington.\nHoglund also distinguished himself\nand the local Reserve by finishing No.\n1 on the class list, not having had any\nmishaps during the entire course.\n(second class) John James\nKlak, 2015 Kalorama road, has been\nordered to the United States Naval\nReserve Air Training Station at\nSquantum, Mass., for a period of\ntraining to fit him for commission as\nan aviator. He is one of five who\nhave been ordered for this duty.\nEnsigns Malcolm M. Cloukey And\nRobert L. Eearle of the local aviation\nNaval Reserve, now on training duty\nat the naval air station at Anacostia,\nD. C., have been granted an exten\nsion of 15 days each on this duty, it\nwas announced at the local Reserve\nheadquarters.\nWilliam Albert Windle has been or\ndered by the Navy Department to be\npromoted from fireman, second- class,\nto machinist's mate, second class. He\nis one of the local Reservists assigned\nto duty as shipkeeper aboard tire\nAllen, and he has the important taste\nof handling the throttle on one of the\nengines.\nJohn Franko, water tender, first\nclass, has been ordered to active duty\nindefinitely, for duty as one of the\nshipkeepers aboard the United States\ndestroyer Allen.\n\nWalker Named Judge.\nWilliam O. Walker, managing edi\ntor of the Tribune, Washington week\nly, has been named by Dr. Robert R.\nMoton, president of the National Ne\ngro Business League of Tuskegee In\nstitute. to serve as a Judge to award\nprizes to the cities w'hich have best,\nobserved National Negro Health week.\nApril 3 to 10, conducted annually un\nder the auspices of the business\nleague.\nSPANISH WAR VETERANS\nElmer M. Case. William C. Stauffer.\nLewis V. Forsythe, Henry G. Darling\nand Louis S. Magruder were mustered\nin at the recent meeting of Richard\nJ. Harden Camp.\nThe report of Department Adjt.\nWilliam I. Jenkins to the recent\ntwenty-eighth annual convention of\nthe Spanish War Veterans showed a\ngain in membership for the year of\n233, bringing the membership in good\nstanding well over the two-thousand\nmark. Department Quartermaster Jo\nseph J. Harvey in his report showed\ntotal receipts to the general fund to\nbe $3,043.51 and expenditures from\nthis fund $2,448.3!). leaving a balance\nin the general fund of $595.12. Th*\nreceipts to the memorial and relief\nfund amounted to $790.41 and the ex\npenditures $407.90, making i balance\nof $292.51. He reported $82.32 balance\nin the Gen. Urell monument fund.\nThe total expenditure from all funds\nwas $2,956.95 and the balance on hand\nis $949.95.\nA. A. Pierce of Gen. Nelson A. Miles\nCamp, chairman of the committee ap\npointed to design a wreath representa\ntive of the United States Spanish War\nVeterans, reported to the convention\nof the Department of the District of\nColumbia, that he had worked in con\njunction with Quartermaster Gen\nJames J. Murphy of the national\nh idquarters and had concluded ar\nrangements for a Spanish War but\nton 8 inches across, available for plac\ning on monuments as well as being\nplaced within wreaths for funerals\nof members of the U. S. W. V. and\nother functions. The stampings are\nto be of thin metal of copper and\nbrass and bronzed over. The stamp\nings will he completed and available\nin about six weeks.\n\nThere are more grapes raised in\nFresno County, California, than in\nany other comparable area in the\nworld, according to an article in the\nLiberty magazine.","height":"27312","width":"20640"}}
